ed with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":24,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":44,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":54,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":64,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert II FitzWalkelyn was born in Radbourne, Derbyshire, England as the son of Robert I FitzWalkelyn of Radbourne. He had at least 3 sons with Mrs. Robert FitzWalkelyn. He died in 1160, in his hometown."},"et":{"–1160":"–1160","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","–1166":"–1166","–Female":"Surnud","1140–1208":"1140–1208","1199–1238":"1199–1238","–1225":"–1225","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1160":"1160","1106":"1106","1238":"1238","1105":"1105","1225":"1225","1135-1160":"1135 kuni 1160","1199":"1199","1166":"1166","1208":"1208","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"–1160":"–1160","1105–Male":"1105–Kuollut","–1166":"–1166","–Female":"Kuollut","1140–1208":"1140–1208","1199–1238":"1199–1238","–1225":"–1225","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1160":"1160","1106":"1106","1238":"1238","1105":"1105","1225":"1225","1135-1160":"vuodesta 1135 vuoteen 1160","1199":"1199","1166":"1166","1208":"1208","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"–1160":"–1160","1105–Male":"1105–Décédé","–1166":"–1166","–Female":"Décédée","1140–1208":"1140–1208","1199–1238":"1199–1238","–1225":"–1225","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1140":"1140","1096":"1096","1160":"1160","1106":"1106","1238":"1238","1105":"1105","1225":"1225","1135-1160":"du 1135 au 1160","1199":"1199","1166":"1166","1208":"1208","Radbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Radbourne, Derbyshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert II FitzWalkelyn est né à Radbourne, Derbyshire, Angleterre, fils de Robert I FitzWalkelyn of Radbourne. Il a eu au moins 3 fils avec Mrs. Robert FitzWalkelyn. Il est décédé en 1160, dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"–1160":"–1160","1105–Male":"